Why is oil cleansing important?​​​​​​​​​
The gentlest way to cleanse your skin is oil cleansing. It’s an easy process that can be very simple, and budget friendly. It gives a deep cleansing by removing all the impurities, bacteria, dead skin cells + even helps to remove blackheads overtime, leaving your skin soft and moisturized.

Some good choices for oil cleansing are:
Castor oil, olive oil, jojoba oil, sweet almond oil, apricot, argan oil, evening primrose, grape seed, sea buckthorn to name a few. You could also mix these at home to create a custom blend.

Holy Basil is said to contain antifungal, antibacterial, anti-inflammatory, and antiviral properties. Studies have shown that Holy Basil can help lower stress, blood pressure and sugar, aid in improving pain and inflammation in the joints, heal wounds in the mouth and on the body, aid the lungs and respiratory system and more.

Some people like to use the oils from the plant especially for topical use. Others tend to drink the tea which is a great way to add this special herb to your everyday ritual. Most health food stores carry the tea, and you can find the plants themselves at smaller farms.

The health of your cells significantly impacts your skin and aging process. Skin cells undergo constant renewal, and factors like a balanced diet, hydration, and protection from UV rays contribute to cell health. Collagen and elastin, crucial for skin elasticity, can be affected by cell damage, leading to wrinkles and loss.of tightness in the skin. Healthy cells also aid in repairing damage caused by environmental factors, promoting a youthful complexion. Conversely, factors like stress, poor nutrition, and sun exposure can accelerate aging by affecting cell function and contributing to the breakdown of collagen and elastin. 

To enhance cell health through nutrition, focus on a diet rich in:

Antioxidants: Found in fruits and vegetables, antioxidants combat oxidative stress and support cellular repair. Berries, spinach, and kale are excellent choices.

Omega-3 Fatty Acids: Found in fatty fish, flaxseeds, and walnuts, these promote cell membrane health and reduce inflammation.

Vitamins and Minerals: Ensure an adequate intake of vitamins A, C, E, and minerals like zinc and selenium. These play crucial roles in cell function and repair.

Protein: Essential for cell structure and repair, include lean sources like organic meats, fish, and beans in your diet.

Hydration: Water is vital for overall cell function and maintaining skin hydration.

Colorful Vegetables: Include a variety of colorful vegetables for a spectrum of nutrients that support cellular health.

Green Tea: Rich in antioxidants, green tea has been associated with various health benefits, including promoting cell health.

Probiotics: Support gut health, influencing overall well-being and potentially benefiting skin health.
